history was at what was probably its lowest ebb. A quarter of a century on, there has been a tremendous broadening of the scope of what the study of empire encompasses. Essays in the volume consider ways in which the series and the wider historiography have sought to reconnect British and imperial histories; to lay bare the cultural expressions and registers of colonial power; and to explore the variety of experiences the home population derived from the empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImperialismxHistoriography. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish Raj.  aBritish colonialism.  aEmpire and Sexuality.  aEmpire of Nature.  aImperialism and the Natural World.  aIndian press.  aJohn MacKenzie.  aMuseums and Empire.  aOrientalism.  aStudies in Imperialism series.  aThird British Empire.  acolonial history.  acolonial policing.  acultural communication.  adecolonisation.  adiasporas.  ahistorical geographies.  aimmigrant welfare.  aimperial histories.  aspatial concepts.1 aAldrich, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmrith, Sunil S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouse, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaul, Chandrika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Dane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeonardi, Cherry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLester, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacKenzie, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSinha, Mrinalini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct